I ended up creating my own sink for this purpose:
```
Sinks.Many&lt;Map&lt;String, List&lt;Object&gt;&gt;&gt; sink = Sinks.many()
    .unicast()
    .onBackpressureBuffer(
          Queues.&lt;Map&lt;String,List&lt;Object&gt;&gt;&gt;get(100).get()
    );
```

With the sink, I&#39;m able to handle the `FAIL_OVERFLOW` errors manually.  In this case, `emitNext` will just retry if the 2nd parameter returns `TRUE`

```
sink.emitNext(retVal, (signalType, emitResult) -&gt; {
  logger.debug(&quot;Got Error At Count [{}] With SignalType: [{}] and EmitResult: [{}]&quot;, currentCount, signalType, emitResult);
  return Sinks.EmitResult.FAIL_OVERFLOW == emitResult;
});
```

Alternately, you can use the `sink.tryEmitNext()` method, which will return the result (possibly a `FAIL_OVERFLOW`) which you can then handle however you&#39;d like. 

Then, to connect it to spring-cloud-stream, I can simply return the sink as a flux:

```
return () -&gt; sink.asFlux()
```

I&#39;m sure there are downsides to this, but in my relatively simple application, this was sufficient.

