A suggested workaround is to wrap the call in a [Spring @Retryable][1] as follows. It will cause a retry when a null is returned. The retry attempts will back-off exponentially.

    public class RedisRetryWrapper {
    
    	@Autowired
    	private RedisTemplate redisTemplate;
    	
    	@Retryable(retryFor = NullReturnException.class, maxAttempts = 5, backoff = @Backoff(delay = 10))
    	public Object opsForHash(Object key, Object hashKey) {
    		Object result = redisTemplate.opsForHash().get(key, hashKey);
    		if (result == null) {
    			throw new NullReturnException();
    		}
    		return result;
    	}
    
    }

`opsForHash` must be called from a class besides `RedisRetryWrapper` to allow the java proxy mechanism to work.

