I think that if you are using reduce-like functions, 
which is basically what you have in the Java stream (Stream.allMatch, Stream.anyMatch and Stream.reduce), you are much better with the atomic two-object comparison function (or conflicting in your case). You can compose any type of comparison/conflict check using these functions very easily.

Furthermore, your 75 lines function seems kinda bloated, in the 8 queens problem (or n-queens), if you use the backtracking algorithm, all you need to do is try to add a queen at a certain point of time and check if it conflicts with other queens. You never need to check conflicts between all the possible queen pairs. 

Regarding the implementation, I think that an arithmetic approach is very elegant. use the coorinates deltas to determine if they have the same diagonal.

    public static boolean areQueensOnSameDiagonal(Queen queen1, Queen queen2) {
        // Calculate delta of x and y coordinates
        int deltaX = Math.abs(queen1.x - queen2.x);
        int deltaY = Math.abs(queen1.y - queen2.y);
        
        // Queens are on the same diagonal if delta of x and y coordinates are the same
        return deltaX == deltaY;
    }

